			<wp:comment_date_gmt>2012-03-01 13:31:00</wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[Ah, I see what you mean about the auto-focus in the search field, Luca. So, this happens only when you're already on the search results page and happens for the large search field at the top of the results. Not the search field at the top right — I still get the auto-focus for that field on the aforementioned pages.
But for the main field, let me analyze this a little bit. That's interesting that you need the autofocus there. We assumed that once you are on the search results, it means you have already got the results for your original query. What you do next is to re-fine or filter the already-got results. But, probably, not make a new search immediately. I personally, don't do that so could be wrong in this assumption — if I get search results, probably, I look through those, maybe re-order or something like that to get what I was looking for. But I don't search again right away. I will think about this and will look for some studies on this topic. Thanks.

